BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wenner-gren-post-phd-research-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260515T142202Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261101
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261102
SUMMARY:Deadline: Wenner-Gren Foundation: Post-PhD Research Grant (November
  2026 cycle)
DESCRIPTION:Research grants from the Wenner-Gren Foundation for individual 
 scholars with a PhD or equivalent to support a discrete project of anthrop
 ological research. The grant supports the project's most substantial cost 
 (typically fieldwork or core research activity) and may be used for direct
  research expenses\; not for salary or institutional overhead. Deadlines a
 re biannual: 1 May and 1 November each year. ELIGIBILITY: scholars who hol
 d a PhD (or equivalent) in anthropology or a clearly related discipline\; 
 nationality and country of work are not restricted. Up to USD 25\,000 per 
 grant. Strictly anthropology focus - the project must be primarily anthrop
 ological in scope and method (sociocultural\, biological\, archaeological 
 or linguistic anthropology\, etc.).\n\nOrganisation: Wenner-Gren Foundatio
 n for Anthropological Research\nLocation: Worldwide (research may take pla
 ce anywhere\; applicant must hold an anthropology PhD or equivalent)\nAwar
 d: Up to USD 25\,000 per grant\nDuration: Project-based\, typically up to 
 24 months of research activity\n\nMore: https://wennergren.org/program/pos
 t-phd-research-grant/
URL:https://wennergren.org/program/post-phd-research-grant/
LOCATION:Worldwide (research may take place anywhere\; applicant must hold 
 an anthropology PhD or equivalent)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:sff-2026-themed-rounds@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260515T142202Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260610
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260611
SUMMARY:Deadline: Survival and Flourishing Fund (SFF): 2026 Themed Rounds (
 Climate\, Animal Welfare\, HSEE)
DESCRIPTION:Recommender-grant rounds (the SFF S-Process) funding work that 
 improves the long-term trajectory of life on Earth\, backed by Jaan Tallin
 n and other donors. Funded cause areas span AI safety\, biosecurity\, clim
 ate\, animal welfare\, and human self-empowerment / existential risk reduc
 tion (HSEE). The 2026 cycle includes the closed Main Round (deadline 22 Ap
 ril 2026) plus three themed rounds with paired Theme and Speculation deadl
 ines: Climate (Theme 10 June\, Speculation 24 June 2026)\; Animal Welfare 
 (Theme 24 June\, Speculation 8 July 2026)\; HSEE (Theme 8 July\, Speculati
 on 22 July 2026). The S-Process is recommender-driven: recommenders indepe
 ndently evaluate applications and the Fund aggregates their recommendation
 s into grant decisions. ELIGIBILITY: primarily registered non-profit organ
 isations and fiscally-sponsored projects\; individual researchers can appl
 y through a fiscal sponsor. Grants typically range from tens of thousands 
 of USD to low millions. Total programme USD 20-40M across all 2026 rounds.
 \n\nOrganisation: Survival and Flourishing Fund (SFF)\, backed by Jaan Tal
 linn\nLocation: Worldwide (grants typically routed through registered non-
 profits\; individual researchers can apply via a fiscal sponsor)\nAward: T
 otal USD 20-40M expected across all 2026 SFF rounds. Individual grants typ
 ically range from tens of thousands of USD to low millions. Remaining 2026
  themed-round deadlines: Climate Theme 10 June\; Climate Speculation and A
 nimal Welfare Theme 24 June\; Animal Welfare Speculation and HSEE Theme 8 
 July\; HSEE Speculation 22 July (HSEE = Human Self-Empowerment and Existen
 tial Risk).\nDuration: Project-based\; recommended grant lengths vary by r
 ound and project\n\nMore: https://survivalandflourishing.fund/2026/applica
 tion
URL:https://survivalandflourishing.fund/2026/application
LOCATION:Worldwide (grants typically routed through registered non-profits\
 ; individual researchers can apply via a fiscal sponsor)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:templeton-rss-intelligence-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260515T142202Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Templeton Foundation: Religion\, Science & Society - Inte
 lligence (2026 cycle)
DESCRIPTION:Religion\, Science & Society (RSS) funding area\, 2026 cycle\, 
 Intelligence track. In alignment with the 2026 Foundation-wide Intelligenc
 e Venture\, RSS welcomes three-year proposals applying theological\, philo
 sophical\, and social-scientific approaches to the guiding themes outlined
  in the venture description. Two scales of project are supported: small\, 
 focused studies under USD $260K\, and larger collaborative initiatives up 
 to USD $2.5M that use subgrants or internal Requests For Proposals to stru
 cture the work. RSS prioritises interdisciplinary teams. Proposals may inc
 lude public-engagement components\, but the primary activities must be res
 earch. Strong fit for projects bringing humanities\, social science\, and 
 theology into dialogue with AI/cognitive science framings of intelligence.
  ELIGIBILITY: The Foundation funds charitable organizations only\; per Tem
 pleton's Apply for a Grant page\, 'individuals or applicants from for-prof
 it companies should not apply' (individuals/for-profits are funded only by
  rare staff invitation). International organizations are eligible\; the Fo
 undation has funded organizations from around the world. US applicants are
  described publicly only as 'charitable organizations' (formal IRS/501(c)(
 3) verification is handled inside the Templeton Portal after the Funding I
 nquiry stage)\; non-US applicants similarly need to be charitable entities
 \, with equivalency handled through the portal. PROCESS: submit an Online 
 Funding Inquiry (OFI) via the Templeton Portal by 15 July 2026\; full prop
 osals are by invitation only after OFI review.\n\nOrganisation: John Templ
 eton Foundation\nLocation: Worldwide (Templeton funds charitable organizat
 ions inside and outside the US)\nAward: Two tiers: focused studies under U
 SD $260K\; larger collaborative initiatives up to USD $2.5M (using subgran
 ts or internal RFP structures).\nDuration: Three years\n\nMore: https://ww
 w.templeton.org/funding-areas/religion-science-and-society
URL:https://www.templeton.org/funding-areas/religion-science-and-society
LOCATION:Worldwide (Templeton funds charitable organizations inside and out
 side the US)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:templeton-rss-meaning-making-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260515T142202Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Templeton Foundation: Religion\, Science & Society - Mean
 ing Making (2026 cycle)
DESCRIPTION:Religion\, Science & Society (RSS) funding area\, 2026 cycle\, 
 Meaning Making track. RSS is especially interested in three-year projects 
 that investigate concrete manifestations of meaning making in a world mark
 ed by rapid social change\, with attention to the practices\, experiences\
 , and transitions that enable people to develop\, sustain\, or renew a lif
 e of meaning. STRICT BUDGET WINDOWS: this track will consider ONLY (1) pro
 jects between USD $700K and $1.5M (and proposals over $1M must use a Reque
 sts For Proposals (RFP) structure with competitively selected subgrants ar
 ound a shared theme)\, or (2) focused studies requesting less than USD $26
 0K on a specific dimension of meaning-making. Proposals outside these wind
 ows will not be considered. RSS prioritises interdisciplinary teams. Propo
 sals may include public-engagement components\, but the primary activities
  must be research. ELIGIBILITY: The Foundation funds charitable organizati
 ons only\; per Templeton's Apply for a Grant page\, 'individuals or applic
 ants from for-profit companies should not apply' (individuals/for-profits 
 are funded only by rare staff invitation). International organizations are
  eligible\; the Foundation has funded organizations from around the world.
  US applicants are described publicly only as 'charitable organizations' (
 formal IRS/501(c)(3) verification is handled inside the Templeton Portal a
 fter the Funding Inquiry stage)\; non-US applicants similarly need to be c
 haritable entities\, with equivalency handled through the portal. PROCESS:
  submit an Online Funding Inquiry (OFI) via the Templeton Portal by 15 Jul
 y 2026\; full proposals are by invitation only after OFI review.\n\nOrgani
 sation: John Templeton Foundation\nLocation: Worldwide (Templeton funds ch
 aritable organizations inside and outside the US)\nAward: Only two project
  sizes accepted in this track: (1) projects between USD $700K and $1.5M (p
 roposals over $1M should use a Requests For Proposals (RFP) structure to s
 upport competitively selected subgrants around a shared theme)\; (2) focus
 ed studies under USD $260K investigating a specific dimension of meaning-m
 aking.\nDuration: Three years\n\nMore: https://www.templeton.org/funding-a
 reas/religion-science-and-society
URL:https://www.templeton.org/funding-areas/religion-science-and-society
LOCATION:Worldwide (Templeton funds charitable organizations inside and out
 side the US)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:templeton-rss-imagined-futures-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260515T142202Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Templeton Foundation: Religion\, Science & Society - Imag
 ined Futures (2026 cycle)
DESCRIPTION:Religion\, Science & Society (RSS) funding area\, 2026 cycle\, 
 Imagined Futures track. RSS is especially interested in three-year project
 s exploring how religious\, philosophical\, and narrative traditions (from
  theology to science fiction) inform a shared sense of imagination and pos
 sibility. In this topical area RSS will prioritise exploratory projects wi
 th a request amount of up to USD $260K and clear\, achievable outputs. Str
 ong fit for speculative\, narrative-driven\, or futures-oriented research 
 that bridges humanities\, religious studies\, and science-fiction studies.
  RSS prioritises interdisciplinary teams. Proposals may include public-eng
 agement components\, but the primary activities must be research. ELIGIBIL
 ITY: The Foundation funds charitable organizations only\; per Templeton's 
 Apply for a Grant page\, 'individuals or applicants from for-profit compan
 ies should not apply' (individuals/for-profits are funded only by rare sta
 ff invitation). International organizations are eligible\; the Foundation 
 has funded organizations from around the world. US applicants are describe
 d publicly only as 'charitable organizations' (formal IRS/501(c)(3) verifi
 cation is handled inside the Templeton Portal after the Funding Inquiry st
 age)\; non-US applicants similarly need to be charitable entities\, with e
 quivalency handled through the portal. PROCESS: submit an Online Funding I
 nquiry (OFI) via the Templeton Portal by 15 July 2026\; full proposals are
  by invitation only after OFI review.\n\nOrganisation: John Templeton Foun
 dation\nLocation: Worldwide (Templeton funds charitable organizations insi
 de and outside the US)\nAward: Priority on exploratory projects with a req
 uest amount up to USD $260K.\nDuration: Three years\n\nMore: https://www.t
 empleton.org/funding-areas/religion-science-and-society
URL:https://www.templeton.org/funding-areas/religion-science-and-society
LOCATION:Worldwide (Templeton funds charitable organizations inside and out
 side the US)
END:VEVENT
